A <b>dendrogram</b> (from <language wordnetid="106282651" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../887/11887.xml">
Greek</link></language>
 <it>dendron</it> "tree", <it>-gramma</it> "drawing") is a <graph wordnetid="107000195" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../560/48560.xml">
tree</link></graph>
 diagram frequently used to illustrate the arrangement of the clusters produced by a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../675/669675.xml">
clustering algorithm</link>.  Dendrograms are often used in <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../353/149353.xml">
computational biology</link> to illustrate the clustering of <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../553/4250553.xml">
gene</link>s.<p>

For a clustering example, suppose this data is to be clustered using <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../932/53932.xml">
Euclidean distance</link> as the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../467/1561467.xml">
distance metric</link>.</p>
<p>

<image location="none" width="150px" src="Clusters.PNG" type="frame">
<caption>

Raw data
</caption>
</image>
</p>
<p>

The <link>
hierarchical clustering</link> dendrogram would be as such:</p>
<p>

<image location="none" width="150px" src="Hierarchical_clustering_diagram.png" type="frame">
<caption>

Traditional representation
</caption>
</image>
</p>
<p>

Here the top row of nodes represent data, and the remaining nodes represent the clusters to which the data belong, and the arrows represent the distance.</p>

